Today's world economy is entwined. International trade in goods, services, and financial assets has grown rapidly. Since factors of production and technologies are different among nations, each country has its own comparative advantages in the production of certain goods and services. Moreover, consumers in different nations have unique incomes and tastes. International trade creates world markets for goods and services by allowing suppliers and demanders to interact. Efficient producers can enlarge their market shares, giving consumers more competitive goods to choose. As a result, the world economy becomes more efficient and its production and consumption sets get larger. Trade facilitates world economic development and raises the overall standard of living. 
